<title>How to speak loud and clear without straining your voice from an ESL perspective</title>
</head>
<body>
<p><i>Content warning: Exercises, Anatomy.</i></p>
<nav>
</nav>
<p>
Whether it is for meetings, presentations, or conversations, speaking with appropriate volume and clarity to be heard is an essential skill that is not usually taught.
Most of the time people assume others can just "raise their voice" and will ask assuming it is enough.
If you receive these comments often, you are probably finding them unhelpful because if you could know how lound you should be and were able to sustain speaking that loud you would probably already be doing it.
Obviously the exception is people insecure about their voice, in which case sorry, this is not for you.
The only thing I can say is that people would rather hear you speak with a shitty voice that struggle to decode what you are saying.<br/>
In this article we will see how to increase your volume and sustain that volume without straining your voice.
And no, pushing more air (including screaming) is NOT the answer, it will be more straining and can injure you.
Pushing more air is one really fucking stupid way to permanently injure your vocal cords.
</p>
<h3>How to know how loud you should be</h3>
<ol>
<li>Initially, judge the volume by estimating distance with the furthest people who should be able to hear you, adjust for ambiant noise and presence of objects in the environment, and go louder than this.</li>
<li>
	Directly ask "am I loud enough, are you hearing me well?".
	It is not a strange question, especially when giving presentations or in meetings.
</li>
<li>
	People may simply tell you that you are not loud enough or they cannot hear you.
	But be careful with this one, people will often stop asking if they do not hear significant improvement after asking once or twice.
</li>
<li>
	Look at people body language, and how they answer you.
	Do they seem to be struggling to understand what you say? If so, you should probably speak louder.
	Do they seem attacked, surprised, or preparing for when you speak? If so, you should probably speak quieter.
</li>
</ol>
<h3>How to increase loudness</h3>
<h4>Trick 1: Open your mouth</h4>
<p>
Your voice comes out of your body from your mouth and nose.
If your mouth is mostly closed it will impede on the volume amplification your mouth is able to provide.
Mostly closed here can be measured with the horizontal and vertical distance of your mouth hole.
Usually vertical distance is the problem, if the distance is smaller than the width of one fingers you should definitely open you mouth more.<br/>
Try speaking normally with two fingers in front of your mouth, what is the vertical distance between your lips when saying vowels?
Then try speaking slowly but opening your mouth by widening the gap between your lower and upper teeth so that your lips are about open to the width of two fingers.
This feels strange, exaggerated, and may even be tiring on the jaw, but this is what you should aim at.
Your jaw is a muscle you can train so use this at you advantage and do this exercise regularly.<br/>
When you feel like you are reaching the correct amount of opening, try increasing the speed you are speaking while maitaining mostly the same opening on vowels.
Continue increasing the speed gradually until you reach what seems to be a decent speech pace.
Speak like that when you can, your jaw should be less tired after some time.<br/>
Congratulations! You are no longer mumbling.
Not only should it increase you volume, it should also increase the clarity of your enunciation.
</p>
<h4>Trick 2: Close your vocal cords</h4>
<p>
Vocal cords are not strings but flaps.
They produce sounds when air is passing between them and making them vibrate.
The closer they are to each other, the less air flow you need to make them vibrate.
Air flow is one of the main factor of vocal fatigue, so not only will closing your cords more make you louder, it will also make you able to sustain an equivalent volume longer than with a bigger opening.
If you have a whispery voice, that is a component of the sound of your voice similar to a whisper or a sigh, you will benefit from this trick the most.
On the contrary if you have a rattly/crackly voice you might just have too much closure, or more likely not enough support but that's for another section.<br/>
While keeping your mouth open (see trick 1) in the same position and without moving your lips or tongue, say any vowel, then whisper it, sigh it, and finally exhale silently.
The difference between these sounds is your vocal cords closure and maybe air flow.
Now inhale and with the same restrictions as the previous exercise try slowly going from a silent exhale to saying the chosen vowel.
Be careful to not push too much air as you will need less and less air flow to keep the same loundness when closing your vocal cords.
Do this until you feel you have a better control over your closure and can transition smoothly.<br/>
Now redo the previous exercise starting from a whisper, to saying the vowel and try still closing further until your voice is rattly/crackly or no sound comes out.
This time pay extra care to not push too much air to get sound when your voice becomes rattly/crackly as this can quickly cause vocal cords injury.
On top of that watch the position of your tongue as it can be the reason you are no longer getting sound, again, your tongue shouldn't move.
Repeat this exercise until you feel you can consistently get to a rattly/crackly sound.<br/>
Now you can control vocal cords closure, so be sure to set your closure level to eliminate whisperiness and optimise air flow against loudness, then speak like this for some time.
It can get tiring but not on your voice hopefully; vocal cords closure is controlled by a muscle that can be train so you should take advantage of this.<br/>
Congratulations! You are no longer whispering.
Not only should it increase you volume, it should also reduce the air flow you need.
Later we will safely adjust air flow for loudness; at some point whisperiness can come back or strain can appear, so be sure you are in control of vocal cords closure and can train to adjust it.
</p>
<h4>Trick 3: Breathe</h4>
<p>
Producing sound requires air, and air pressure is better controlled if your lungs are neither near full or near empty.
On top of that breathing through the nose is recommended over breathing through the mouth (unless you are singing, but this is not the goal here even if most tricks here can be used for singing too).
This means you should inhale enough air through your nose frequently enough, and not try to cram as much words as possible on a single breathing cycle.<br/>
