transform the sentence below into an exercise/diagnostic or merge with first paragraph
If you fall short of air in the middle of sentences, rattling/crackling appears near the end of your sentences, or you are spending air quickly you will benefit from this trick.
</p>
<h4>Trick 4: Use a pitch in the middle of your range</h4>
<p>
Loudness decreases at constant effort as pitch approaches the limits of our range.
Equivalently to get the same loudness you need to spend more energy and are at higher risk of injury at the edges of your range.<br/>
Try saying a word normally and lock in on a non diphtong vowel (ex: perpendiiiii), then increase your pitch, go back to normal and lower your pitch.
While doing so, if you need to inhale, be sure to restart the sound the same way you stopped; you may switch register otherwise.
Did you notice change in loudness or effort?
How far can you go?
Is there a direction you can go significantly easier than the other?
If so, you should change your base pitch to that easier spot.<br/>
Try remembering this pitch.
Then try speaking and moving to that pitch after the first word, then adjusting every word after that.
If you adjust in one word at most, try starting at the loud pitch now.<br/>
You don't have to always speak with this pitch, but when you think loud you should think about this pitch.
</p>
